<p>The data above reflects some of the largest numbers of students utilizing mental health services than there have been in years. The declining state of students‚Äô mental health pre-pandemic definitely can have an effect on how they personally handled the isolation and stress that came with it. This is why the 2021-2022 school year, which has been mostly in person for many schools, can indicate the ways in which the virus could‚Äôve hindered their progress. 
In the AUCCCD survey of 2020-2021, however, results looked much different than the years prior. Only about 8.6% of any school‚Äôs student body was reported to be using counseling services. 
The majority of centers saw a decrease in demand during 2020-2021, 3% saw no change, and less than one-third of centers saw an increase in demand. Reasoning for this can be attributed to the fact that nearly <a href="https://nces.ed.gov/whatsnew/press_releases/06_16_2021.asp">84%</a> of institutions switched to online learning during this time. Because of this, many students were home and disincentivized from seeking online help. 
This could also have to do with accessibility issues that student‚Äôs faced in getting in touch with their school‚Äôs mental health services. Students who felt disconnected from their schools and didn‚Äôt know enough about their services perhaps didn‚Äôt know to reach out or that that was an option for them.</p>

