<p>Based on this data, it is seen that there is a trend with smaller schools treating a larger population of their student body as opposed to bigger schools. This could be due to lack of accessibility provided at l
In 2020, The American Psychological Association conducted a <a href="https://www.apa.org/news/press/releases/2020/11/telehealth-survey-summary.pdf">survey</a> in which they found a 74% increase in psychologists treating patients with anxiety disorders and a 60% increase in treating those with depressive disorders. Based on this information from years ago, this could show an attempted switch from campus counseling centers to private practices.</p>

<h2 id="american-university-counseling-center-example">American University Counseling Center Example</h2>
<p>Recalling his experience in trying to get in contact with American University‚Äôs counseling center, a student by the name of Gage (class of 2024) said that he waited over a month to hear back from them in order to schedule a preliminary appointment. ‚ÄúIt was just really frustrating,‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúI needed help and I felt like they didn‚Äôt even care enough to get back to me.‚Äù 
Fanta Aw, the Vice President of Campus Life &amp; Inclusive Excellence at American University (AU) issued a <a href="https://www.american.edu/ocl/s2020-mental-health.cfm">statement</a> in 2020 regarding the then current state of their counseling services. In it, they said, ‚ÄúSatisfaction scores for the Center are high, with 97.5% reporting they would recommend the Counseling Center to a friend.‚Äù However, they went on to say, ‚Äúa number of students have frustrations related to access√â Around 20% of all appointments made at the Counseling Center this Fall were not attended.‚Äù 
After calling AU‚Äôs counseling center to see how these numbers had changed over the 2021-2022 school year, they were unable to respond. 
Additionally, the office of the Dean of Students at AU has consistently said that they are supportive of assisting students with their academic responsibilities (providing they can provide proper documentation of mental health issues). In regards to how the Dean of Students handled her mental health issues in the spring of 2022, Angelina (sophomore, class of 2024) said, ‚ÄúAlthough the dean was extremely kind, I ultimately was left doing the work to make sure I had the accommodations I need, even though I provided a note from a psychiatrist.‚Äù She continued by saying, ‚ÄúIt was my teachers who actually helped me√â the dean actually just stressed me out and caused me to [do] extra work that didn‚Äôt serve a purpose.‚Äù</p>

<h2 id="conclusion">Conclusion</h2>
<p>Though the world has truly begun to open back up (so to speak), many are still handling the ways in which the pandemic has affected them and their mental health. Specifically for students, it is very overwhelming to reenter academia after being apart from it for so long. Despite the fact that things are going back to ‚Äúnormal‚Äù, it is imperative that universities and colleges continue to be sympathetic to students suffering from mental health issues following the pandemic. Despite the decrease of services in the 2020-2021 school year, these institutions must still have the goal of ensuring their students overall well being and not just with academics.</p>

